Part I - Prosper loan Dataset¶

by Zainab Mustapha¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains data on 113,937 loan from 2005 to 2014 with 81 variables on each loancopy. These variables include loan amount, borrower rate, loan status, borrower income, prosper rating and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has about 113,937 rows and 81 coulumns. The columns mostly contain numerical values in both integer and float formats. There are also datetime objects. The column labels are descriptive. Notably, some columns contain null values. Overall, the data frame presents different details about the loan borrowers and lender.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Combination of visual and programmatic assessments, and review of dataset documentation makes the following features more interesting in drawing conclusions about the dataset. loan status, lender yield, prosper rating, prospser score, borrower APR, loan amount, is borrower home owner or not, state of borrower, income range of borrowers, and employment status.

Questions posed¶

  1. What factors affect a loan’s outcome status?
  2. What affects the borrower’s APR?
  3. What factors affect loan amount?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

BorrowerRate, BorrowerAPR, EstimatedLoss, ProsperScore, ListingCatgory, Occupation, Employmentstatus, employment status duration, isborrowerhomeowner, income range, loan original amount, loan term, listingcategory

           'Not available': 'Other' }

# Function to apply
def emply_status(loancopy):
    if loancopy['EmploymentStatus'] in status.keys():
        description = status[loancopy['EmploymentStatus']]
        return description
    else:
        return loancopy['EmploymentStatus']

           2: 'Home Improvement', 3:'Business', 
           4: 'Personal loan', 6: 'Auto', 
           13: 'Household Expenses', 15: 'Medical/Dental'}

# Function to apply
def listing_key(loancopy):
    if loancopy['ListingCategory (numeric)'] in listing.keys():
        fulldescription = listing[loancopy['ListingCategory (numeric)']]
        return fulldescription
    else:
        return 'others'

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The borrower rate and borrower APR follow a bimodal distribution pattern, ranging from 0.1 to 0.4. Loan amounts range from approximately 1,000 to 35,000 dollars, with most loans falling within the 1,000 to 15,000 dollars range. The majority of loans are currently ongoing, with a significant number already completed and only a few past due. Home ownership is split equally between owners and non-owners. The majority of loans have a 36-month term, with a small proportion having a 12-month term. The most common listing category for Prosper loans is debt consolidation, accounting for about half of all loans. Other categories include home improvement, business, auto, and household expenses. The distribution of borrowers by state shows the highest number of borrowers are California residents, while the least number of borrowers are from North Dakota. However, borrowers come from all 50 states in the US. Finally, a large number of borrowers fall within the income range of 25,000 to 74,999 dollars.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The loan amount distribution initially appeared heavily right-skewed, but after adjusting the bin size, the distribution showed less skewness. To address missing values in the BorrowerAPR column, median APR was used as a replacement. However, this replacement did not significantly alter the data distribution. To simplify the data on employment status, categories such as employed, full-time, self-employed, and part-time were grouped together under the 'employed' category. The listingCategory column was converted from numeric to text, and certain categories were merged for easier analysis.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The relationship between APR and loan amount does not show any clear dependencies, with varying APRs across different loan amounts. This calls for further investigation, as seen in the multivariate exploration. However, a linear relationship between APR and interest rate is evident, with higher interest rates leading to higher APRs.

A plot of loan amount vs. listing category shows that the highest loan amounts were taken out for debt consolidation, followed by business loans.

Analysis of the relationship between employment status and loan status reveals that more loans are granted to the employed than to the unemployed.

Borrowers within the income range of 25,000 to 100,000 dollars received the highest loan amounts.

The higher a borrower's prosper score (creditworthiness), the higher their loan amount. Borrowers with lower prosper scores (1.0 and 2.0) received the least amount of loan. However, there were some outliers, receiving as much as $25,000 in loan. A plot of prosper rating vs. loan amount shows a similar trend, with lower prosper scores not necessarily implying a low prosper rating, as both are based on different criteria.

Plots of APR vs. prosper score and prosper rating show that better creditworthiness leads to lower APR, while higher risk loans lead to higher APR.

A plot of loan status against prosper rating shows that there are not many active high-risk and low-risk loans, potentially due to the limited number of such loans to begin with. There are only about 5,000 low-risk loans (AA) and almost 7,500 high-risk loans (HR). However, high-risk loans have higher default and charged-off rates when compared with low-risk loans, which have substantially lower counts for defaulted and charged-off loans.

Most defaulted and charged-off loans have a term of 36 months.

Definitely the multivariate plot of APR against loan amount and prosper rating further strengthened the dependance of APR on creditworthiness. It also shows that lesser dollar amount of loan was given out to less credit worthy borrowers. The reverse is true for credit worthy borrowers.

Conclusions¶

The loan dataset has variables such as borrower rate, borrower APR, loan amount, loan status, home ownership, loan term, listing category, income range, and prosper score. The data set did not require much wrangling efforts as it appears pretty much tidy and clean. Since the APR column contains some null values, they were filled with median calues across the dataset. Employment statuses were re-classified and listing categories were mapped from numeric values to texts.

The loan amount ranges from 1,000 to 35,000 dollars, with most loans falling within the 1,000 to 15,000 dollars range. The borrower rate and APR show a bimodal distribution. The loan status shows that most loans are still ongoing, with a smaller number past due or completed. The highest number of borrowers are in California, while North Dakota has the least. The borrowers' income range mostly falls within 25,000 to 74,999 dollars.

There is a linear relationship between APR and interest rate, with higher interest rates leading to higher APR. Loans for debt consolidation and business have the highest loan amount, while employed individuals received higher loan amount than unemployed individuals. Borrowers with higher prosper scores tend to get higher loan amounts. The plots of APR vs prosper score and prosper rating show that better creditworthiness is associated with lower APR. High-risk loans have a higher default and charged-off rate compared to low-risk loans. Most defaulted and charged off loans have a 36-month term.

An interesting feature that was not explored would be the factors affecting prosper score and prosper rating. Is this dependent on the borrower or on the use of the loans. This would be interesting to know.
